**Intuition:**

Both C++ and Python provide built-in methods that compare sequences (e.g. vectors or lists) lexicographically by default. This means that when you sort a list of sequences:


The first elements are compared.
If they are equal, the second elements are compared.
The process continues until a difference is found or one sequence runs out of elements.
**C++ Implementation:**

In C++, if you store each line as a `vector&lt;int&gt;`, the default `&lt;` operator performs lexicographical comparison. Therefore, you can simply use `std::sort` without any custom comparator. The logic flow is:


Read the integer NNN (number of lines).
For each line, read integers until you encounter −1-1−1.
Store the numbers in a `vector&lt;int&gt;`.
Sort the collection of vectors.
Output the sorted sequences.
Below is the C++ code for this approach:

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;algorithm&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    vector&lt;vector&lt;int&gt;&gt; lines;

    while (N--) {
        vector&lt;int&gt; nums;
        int x;
        while (cin &gt;&gt; x &amp;&amp; x != -1) {
            nums.push_back(x);
        }
        lines.push_back(nums);
    }

    // Default lexicographical sorting of vectors
    sort(lines.begin(), lines.end());

    // Output the sorted lines
    for (auto &amp;vec : lines) {
        for (auto &amp;num : vec) {
            cout &lt;&lt; num &lt;&lt; " ";
        }
        cout &lt;&lt; "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
`**Python Implementation:**

Python lists are compared lexicographically by default. The steps are similar:


Read NNN from input.
For each of the next NNN lines, read and convert the numbers (ignoring the trailing −1-1−1) into a list.
Sort the list of lists.
Print the sorted lists.
The Python code for this approach is as follows:

`def main():
    import sys
    data = sys.stdin.read().strip().splitlines()
    if not data:
        return
    N = int(data[0])
    all_lines = []
    for line in data[1:N+1]:
        # Convert to integers and ignore the last element (-1)
        nums = list(map(int, line.split()))[:-1]
        all_lines.append(nums)

    # Default lexicographical sort
    all_lines.sort()

    for nums in all_lines:
        print(" ".join(map(str, nums)))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
`**Intuition:**

Although the default sorting works well, it is educational to know how to implement a custom comparator that mimics lexicographical order. This can be useful in scenarios where you need to alter or explicitly define the comparison logic. The idea is to compare two sequences element by element:


Iterate over both sequences up to the length of the shorter one.
At the first index where the numbers differ, decide the order.
If all compared elements are equal, the sequence with fewer numbers comes first.
**C++ Implementation:**

We define a custom comparator function `lexCompare` to compare two `vector&lt;int&gt;` objects manually and then pass it to `std::sort`.

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;algorithm&gt;
using namespace std;

bool lexCompare(const vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; a, const vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; b) {
    int n = min(a.size(), b.size());
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
        if (a[i] &lt; b[i])
            return true;
        if (a[i] &gt; b[i])
            return false;
    }
    return a.size() &lt; b.size();
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    vector&lt;vector&lt;int&gt;&gt; lines;
    while (N--) {
        vector&lt;int&gt; nums;
        int x;
        while (cin &gt;&gt; x &amp;&amp; x != -1) {
            nums.push_back(x);
        }
        lines.push_back(nums);
    }

    // Sort using the custom lexicographical comparator
    sort(lines.begin(), lines.end(), lexCompare);

    // Output the sorted lines
    for (auto &amp;vec : lines) {
        for (auto num : vec)
            cout &lt;&lt; num &lt;&lt; " ";
        cout &lt;&lt; "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
`**Python Implementation:**

In Python, you can use the `functools.cmp_to_key` function to convert a custom comparator into a key function for sorting. Here is how you can implement a custom comparator:

`from functools import cmp_to_key

def lex_compare(a, b):
    n = min(len(a), len(b))
    for i in range(n):
        if a[i] &lt; b[i]:
            return -1
        elif a[i] &gt; b[i]:
            return 1
    return -1 if len(a) &lt; len(b) else (1 if len(a) &gt; len(b) else 0)

def main():
    import sys
    data = sys.stdin.read().strip().splitlines()
    if not data:
        return
    N = int(data[0])
    all_lines = []
    for line in data[1:N+1]:
        # Convert to integers and ignore the trailing -1
        nums = list(map(int, line.split()))[:-1]
        all_lines.append(nums)

    # Sort using a custom comparator
    all_lines.sort(key=cmp_to_key(lex_compare))

    for nums in all_lines:
        print(" ".join(map(str, nums)))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
`
